The '''Carolina Panthers''' are a professional [[American football]] team based in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]. They play in the [[NFC South|southern division]] of the [[National Football Conference]] (NFC), one of the two conferences in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). The team is worth approximately [[United States dollar|USD]] $1 billion, according to ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref name="Valuation" /> and is controlled by [[Jerry Richardson]] and his family; they have a 48% stake. The remainder of the team is held by a group of 14 [[Limited partnership|limited partners]]. The head coach is [[Ron Rivera]], while the president is [[Danny Morrison (sports executive)|Danny Morrison]].

The Panthers first competed in 1995 and fared well in their first two years, finishing {{Win-loss record|w=7|l=9}} in 1995 (an all-time best for an expansion NFL team's first season) and {{Win-loss record|w=12|l=4}} in 1996. They did not have another winning season until 2003, when the team won the [[NFC Championship Game]] and reached [[Super Bowl XXXVIII]], losing 32–29 to the [[New England Patriots]]. The Panthers have made the playoffs four times, reaching the NFC Championship Game in three of them. They have won three division titles, one of them in the [[NFC West]] and two of them in the NFC South. The team's most recent playoff appearance was in 2008, when the Panthers finished {{Win-loss record|w=12|l=4}} before losing to the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in the divisional round. The team failed to record another winning season until [[2013 NFL season|2013]] following a 2012 season that ended with a {{Win-loss record|w=7|l=9}} record.

The Carolina Panthers are legally registered as Panthers Football, LLC.<ref name="Panthers Football, LLC">{{cite web|url=http://www.secretary.state.nc.us/corporations/Corp.aspx?PitemId=4969201#|title=Panthers Football, LLC|publisher=North Carolina Department of the Secretary of State|date=January 1, 2000|accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> The team is headquartered in [[Bank of America Stadium]], located in [[Charlotte center city|uptown Charlotte]]; the stadium also serves as the team's [[Home (sports)|home field]]. The Panthers are one of the few teams in the NFL to own the stadium they play in, which is legally registered as Panthers Stadium, LLC.<ref name="Panthers Stadium, LLC">{{cite web|url=http://www.secretary.state.nc.us/corporations/Corp.aspx?PitemId=5486354|title=Panthers Stadium, LLC|publisher=North Carolina Department of the Secretary of State|date=July 16, 2002|accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> The Panthers are supported throughout [[the Carolinas]]; although the team has played their home games in Charlotte since the completion of their stadium in 1996, they played home games in [[Clemson, South Carolina]], during their first season, and they host their annual [[training camp]] in [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]]. At home games, the atmosphere has been described as comparable to that of other NFL teams, with some games playing host to a large number of fans of the opposing team; this has been attributed to several factors, such as the city's relatively recent entry into the NFL, the popularity of [[basketball]] in the Charlotte region, and the large number of Charlotte residents who are originally from other cities with NFL teams. The Panthers' uniforms consist of black, white, and blue jerseys paired with white and silver pants, a pattern which has only seen minor changes since the team's inception. The team maintains rivalries with the three other teams in the NFC South, in addition to having out-of-division rivalries with the Arizona Cardinals and [[Dallas Cowboys]].

==History==
{{Further|History of the Carolina Panthers}}
